Answers

b. There are 4 columns, so there are 4 variables.
c.Â The only numerical column/variable is Age.
d.Â The categorical columns/variables are Academic Standing, Candidate Choice, and Male.
e. In the Male column, 1 means the student is male, and 0 means the student is not male.

Question 7.
a. Minimum = 203, Q1 = 212, medium = 216, Q3 = 221, maximum = 231
b. Q3 for Chinstrap penguins is (roughly) 201, so the approximately 25% of Chinstrap penguins had flipper length greater than 201 mm.
c.Â Q1 = 186 and Q3 = 195, thus the middle 50% of the Adelie penguins have flipper lengths ranged from 186 mm to 195 mm.
d.Â Without computing the IQR explicitly for each species, we can see that the IQR (the colored portion of the boxes) is roughly equal across species. So the variation of flipper length is roughly equal for all three species.

Question 8.
a. Histogram
b. Left-skewed
c.Â \(0.06 + 0.02 + 0.02 = 0.1\), so 10% of the students scored less than 60% on the test.
d.Â \((0.44 + 0.27) \cdot 52 = 36.92\), so approximately 37 students had a score of 80% or above.
e. The median and IQR are the best measure for center and spread, respectively.
f.Â mean < median g. The mean will lower, but the median will remain the same.

Question 9.
a. Because the data is symmetric and unimodal, the empirical rule applies.
b. The sample mean of $100 represents the average price of the 50 video game consoles sampled.
c.Â On average, the price of a console is $100 from the mean price of $500.
d.Â \(x = 350\), \(\bar{x} = 500\), \(s = 100\), \[ z = \frac{x - \bar{x}}{s} = \frac{350 - 500}{100} = \frac{-150}{100} = -1.5 \] The price of $350 is 1.5 standard deviations below the mean price of $500.
e. \(x = 700\), \(\bar{x} = 500\), \(s = 100\), \[ z = \frac{x - \bar{x}}{s} = \frac{700 - 500}{100} = \frac{200}{100} = 2. \] The price of $700 is 2 standard deviations above the mean price of $500.
f.Â According to the empirical rule, 68% of the data is within 1 standard deviation from the mean: \[ (\bar{x} - s, \bar{x} + s) = (500 - 100, 500 + 100) = (\$400, \$600) \] g. According to the empirical rule, 95% of the data is within 2 standard deviations from the mean: \[ (\bar{x} - 2s, \bar{x} + 2s) = (500 - 2 \cdot 100, 500 + 2 \cdot 100) = (500 - 200, 500 + 200) = (\$300, \$700) \]
h. According to the empirical rule, 99.7% of the data is within 3 standard deviations from the mean: \[ (\bar{x} - 3s, \bar{x} + 3s) = (500 - 3 \cdot 100, 500 + 3 \cdot 100) = (500 - 300, 500 + 300) = (\$200, \$800) \]

Question 10.
a. The range (807, 1249) is one standard deviation below and above the mean; by the empirical rule, approximately 68% of all scores fall within this range.

b. The range (586, 1479) is two standard deviations below and above the mean; by the empirical rule, approximately 95% of all scores fall within this range.

c.Â Since the data is unimodal and symmetric, the mean score is roughly the same as the median score, therefore, 50% of all scores are greater than 1028.

d.Â The regions of interest are shaded in pink. Note that these two regions are complementary to the region from part a. This means the two regions must have a combined percentage of \(100 - 68 = 32\%\). Since the distribution is symmetric, the left and the right shaded regions must be equal, so each region accounts for \(32/2 = 16\%\) of total scores.

e. The region of interest in this instance is the left shaded region from part d.Â So approximately 16% of the total scores are less than 807.

f.Â According to the empirical rule, approximately 95% of the data falls within 2 standard deviations from the mean, the plot is the same as that of part b. Thus the two scores are 586 and 1470.

g. We have \(x = 1300\), \(\bar{x} = 1028\), with \(s = 221\). So the z-score is \[z = \frac{x - \bar{x}}{s} = \frac{1300 - 1028}{221} \approx 1.23.\] So Amyâs test score is roughly 1.23 standard deviations above the mean.
